In Hasit Trivedi‚Äôs opinion too, responsible AI will be ‚Äúa long process, and it will not be easy‚Äù, but it certainly will be rooted in accountability and explainability.
We believe the best strategy for implementing AI will vary among organizations, and it could only be formulated through a trial and error method.

But, who is responsible for promoting Responsible AI?

Policy-makersüë¨
Startups‚öíÔ∏è
Every stakeholder using/adopting AIü§ù

Big companies are calling for the responsible use of AI, Governmental policies and regulations are in place, and independent organizations are also spreading awareness on the importance of responsible use of this emerging technology.
Though the advantages and advancements in human-machine interaction have evolved with time, there are still some roadblocks on the way.

On the other hand, explainability is another significant parameter in the adoption of responsible AI. An organization that fails to advocate may lose its customers‚Äô trust. Hence, this concept of responsible AI should be fed into the grassroots of AI development.‚¨ÜÔ∏è

Commenting on the responsible use of AI, Hasit says, ‚ÄúAI is exciting, but it can be dangerous‚Äù. In his opinion, it is a relief that organizations are aware of the dangers that the irresponsible use of technology can bring and are including restrictions through policy frameworks.

You will be delighted to know that the emergence of AI has eradicated language barriers around the worldüíØ

Hasit conveys a thought, ‚ÄúNot once have machines taken over the role of a man. On the other hand, the number of jobs has increased due to the invention of new machines‚Äù.

‚ÄúSpeech and vision are the two game-changing pieces AI provided on this front‚Äù, stated Hasit Trivedi.
